10:31](../../../bib/kjv/act010.htm#031.md); When Nehemiah had prayed for
the relief of his countrymen, and perhaps in David's words, [Psa
51:18](../../../bib/kjv/psa051.htm#018.md), he did not sit still and say,
"Let God now do his own work, for I have no more to do;" but set himself
to do what he could towards it; and here we find that the people were of
one heart with Nehemiah. Our prayers must be seconded with our serious
endeavours, or else we mock God. Nearly four months had passed, namely,
from Chisleu to Nisan (November to March), before Nehemiah made his
application to the king for leave to go to Jerusalem; either because the
winter was not a proper time for such a journey, and he would not make a
motion till he could pursue it, or because it was so long before his
month of waiting upon the king came, and there was no coming into his
presence until called for, [Est 4:11](../../../bib/kjv/est004.htm#011.md).
We are not thus limited to certain moments in our addresses to the King
of kings, but have liberty of access to him at all times; to the throne
of grace we never come unseasonably.

